VSri Lakshmi Nrisimha Seva Samithi organised a five-day music festival to raise funds for the renovation of the old temple of Sri Lakshmi Nrisimha Swamy in Secunderabad.The five-day fest began with a scintillating vocal recital by noted musician Nithyashri Mahadevan, who is the grand-daughter of D.K. Pattamal.  Her voice modulation and good control over thesancharasat thetara sthaiis noteworthy.She began her recital with CharukesiVarnamin Tamil.Innum maniawith rhythmiclayapatterns was good.Sri Narasimhawas the next to come as it was aptly chosen for the occasion in theragamPhala Ranjani and it was neatly rendered. Kannada Gowla was taken for a delightful  expansion for Thyagaraja&#8217;sOrajhoopu chu chediwith crispyswaramand itset the tempo of the concert. Poorvikalyani was taken for a detailed expansion and theragamhad all the classicsangathisandGnana mosagaradain Rupakam withneravalat his best and synchronisingswaracombinations was enjoyable.Samiki sari evvari,a Tamil composition in Kedaragowla was sung neatly. Dwijhavanthi was taken next for Deekshitar&#8217;sAkhilandeswariand it was melodiously rendered by Nityakeeping theragabhavamin tact. Bhilahari was the main attraction and theragampart came out cleanly with all the importantsancharasappearing vividly. Thekalapramanawas bit fast and thepathanatharawas also unconventional unlike the yesteryear great masters.Swarakalpanawas well distributed among the four percussionists. A violin recital by seasonedvidwanM.A. Krishna Swamy added lustre to the concert.  The percussion combination of Mannarkoi. J. Balaji on  mridangam, Nemani on ghatam, Shyam on kanjeera took the concert to new heights with their good coordination. Thetaniby all the four was apt and effective. Finally Nithyashri concluded her recital withNamo Namo Narasimhain Shivaranjani followed by aragamalikaandviruttam. Adideva of Annamacharya  in Sindhubhairavi was a melodious rendition followed by aThillanain Dwijavanthi.
